Authored important decretal of 386 (written to Bishop Himerius of Tarragona), commanding celibacy for priests, the first decree on this subject.
of Berber descent. the last pope to have been born on the continent of Africa. The first pope called the "Vicar of Christ"
of Greek descent. Earliest pope not canonized by either the Latin Church or the Eastern Church.

Son of Pope Hormisdas before he became a priest.

of Greek ethnicity. The last pope from Palestine. the only pope to have been a native of Jerusalem.

of Greek ethnicity. The only pope who came from Asia Minor.
of Greek ethnicity. The second pope to bear the same name as his immediate predecessor.
Born as subject of the Rashidun Caliphate. Was Syrian.
Last pope to visit Greece until John Paul II in 2001

Born as subject of the Umayyad Caliphate; the last pope from Syria. The third pope to come from a Muslim country. The third pope to bear the same name as his immediate predecessor. Last pope to have been born outside Europe until the election of Francis in 2013.
later the sovereign of the independent Papal States. Sometimes called Stephen III. The Donation of Pepin. Brother of Paul I.
Erroneously also known as Martin II.
Adrian I was possibly his ancestor.
In early 897 posthumously executed following the Cadaver Synod. His body was reburied with full Christian honours in 897.
"Saeculum obscurum" begins. The first pope to be depicted with the Papal Tiara.
Last to use a new and non-composed regnal name until Francis (2013-)
Probably, according to the Liber Pontificalis and Liutprand of Cremona, the son of Pope Sergius III, and not of Alberic I of Spoleto, who was Marozia's husband.
Erroneously also known as Martin III.
Third pope not to use his personal name (Octavian). Deposed in 963 by Emperor Otto invalidly; end of the "Saeculum obscurum". Possibly murdered in 964.
Elected by the people of Rome, in opposition to Leo VIII who was appointed by Emperor Otto; he accepted his own deposition in 964 leaving Leo VIII as the sole pope.
His pontificate from 963 to 964 is considered illegitimate by today's Catholic Church
Chronicled after his death as "the Good".
Fourth pope not to use his personal name.
The first pope to formally canonize a saint.
the first official German pope and fifth not to use his personal name (Bruno). Henceforth, this decision became tradition among future popes.
the first French (Occitan) pope. He is said to be the first in Christian Europe (outside of Al-Andalus) to introduce the decimal numeral system using the Hindu-Arabic numeral system.
First pope born after the Papal States became a state of the Holy Roman Empire in 962.

column17: Born as a French citizen, of Italian ethnicity, later became a subject of the Papal States and finally an Italian citizen.Had the third-longest reign after Pius IX, and John Paul II. first pope to fully embrace the concept of Mary as mediatrix. column14: Giovanni Battista Enrico Antonio Maria Montini
column17: Last pope to be crowned. First pope since 1809 to travel outside Italy.
Abolished the coronation and opted for the papal inauguration. First pope to use 'the First' in papal name; first with two names for two immediate predecessors. Last pope to use the sedia gestatoria.

first pope of Slavic origin. First non-Italian pope since Adrian VI (1522–1523). Travelled extensively, visiting 129 countries during his pontificate. Second-longest reign after Pius IX. Canonized more saints than all his predecessors. Youngest individual to start his papacy since Pius IX (1846).

Oldest to become pope since Clement XII (1730). Elevated the Tridentine Mass to a more prominent position and promoted the use of Latin; re-introduced several disused papal garments. Authorized the creation of Anglican ordinariates (2009). First pope to renounce the papacy on his own initiative since Celestine V (1294),[47] becoming pope emeritus.[48] Longest-lived pope on record.

First pope to be born outside Europe since Gregory III (731–741) and the first from the Americas; first pope from the Southern Hemisphere. First pope from a religious institute since Gregory XVI (1831–1846); first Jesuit pope. First to use a new and non-composed regnal name since Lando (913–914). First pope to visit and celebrate a mass on the Arabian Peninsula.
